The numerous divisione of Roman actions found in the fourth book of Gaius are based almost entirely on the structure of the intentio; for this being the part of the formula in which we lind, expressly or impliedly, the right alleged by the plaintiff‚ it is by reference to it that we are enabled to distinguish actions according to the rights which they are designed to protect. If the intentio of one formula differs substantially iu structure from that of another, we know at once that the actions themselves, and the rights which they respectively protect, are substantially different as well.

Theprincipal divisions of actions, so far as they arise from differ· ences of structure in the intentio, are as follow.

i. The intentio is either directed against the person of the defend· aut, and names him (e. g. si paret Aulum Agerium Numerio Negidio sestertium x millia dare oportere), orit merely specifies the object to which the plaintiffs claim relates (e. g. si paret Auli Agerii hominem, fundum‚hereditatem‚ ius utendi fruendiesse). In the firstlcase the action is in personam, and brought to enforce an obligation 3 itis called ‘actio ' κατ’ ἐξοχῆν (p. 33² supr). In the second case it is in rem, and asserts either ownership or a ius in re aliena as belonging to the plaintiff ; its specihc name is vindicatio or petitio. A real action claiming a servitude was called actio (in rem) confessoria; one denying the right of another person was called negativa or negatoria

ii. Certain actions in personam are divided into certae and incertae, according as the act claimed by the plaintiff relates to a certum (res or pecunia) or an incertum. In the former case-if, that isto say, the obligation oi the defendant was to pay an ascertained sum of money, or to transfer a res or a definite amount of some res, such as corn, wine, or oil, the intentio ran ‘si paret (reum). . . dare oportere ;’ and if the certum were money, the action was substantially idenrical with the old condictio under the lex Silia, and involved a penal sponsio and restipulatio of a third of the sum in dispute. ln the latter case—if, ¹ that is to say, the obligatiou of the defendant was incertum, i. e. not to transfer such or such res or pecunia, but to perform some other personal act or service-the proper word for the interitio was not dare, but facere, though the two were here usually combined, so that the intentio ran ‘quicquid paret N.
